Rouche, Open Mapping, and Maximum Modulus

Theorem (Rouche’s Theorem)
Suppose \(f, g\) are holomorphic in \(D_r(z_0)\) and \({\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert} > {\left\lvert {g(z)} \right\rvert}\) on \({{\partial}}D_r(z_0)\). Then \(f\) and \(f+g\) have the same number of zeros in \(D_r(z_0)\).
Proof
Let \(f_t(z) = f(z) + tg(z)\) and use the argument principle.
Theorem (Open Mapping Theorem (Stein 4.4))
If \(f\) is holomorphic and nonconstant then \(f\) is an open map.
Proof
Let \(w_0 \in \operatorname{im}({(})f)\) and say \(f(z_0) = w_0\). We want to show that all \(w\) near \(w_0\) are also in \(\operatorname{im}({(})f)\). Define \(g(z) = f(z) - w = f(z) - w_0 + w_0 - w \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}= F(z) + G(z)\).

Now choose \(\delta>0\) such that \(D_\delta(z_0) \subset \Omega\) and \(f(z) \neq w_0\) on \({{\partial}}D_\delta(z_0)\). We then select \(\delta\) such that \({\left\lvert {f(z) - w_0} \right\rvert} \geq \varepsilon> 0\) on \({{\partial}}D_\delta(z_0)\). We have \({\left\lvert {F(z)} \right\rvert} = {\left\lvert {f(z) - w_0} \right\rvert} \geq \varepsilon\).

Now choose \(w\) such that \({\left\lvert {G(z)} \right\rvert} = {\left\lvert {w-w_0} \right\rvert} < \varepsilon\), nothing that \(G(z)\) is a constant function (?). Then \({\left\lvert {F(z)} \right\rvert} \geq \varepsilon> {\left\lvert {w-w_0} \right\rvert} = {\left\lvert {G(z)} \right\rvert}\). So apply Rouche’s theorem and conclude that there exists \(z\in D_\delta(z_0)\) such that \(f(z) = w\).

Qual alert, some questions related to the Open Mapping Theorem.

Theorem (Stein 4.5: Maximum Modulus)
If \(f\) is holomorphic and nonconstant on \(\Omega\), then \({\left\lvert {f} \right\rvert}\) can not attain a maximum in \(\Omega\).
Proof
Suppose toward a contradiction that \({\left\lvert {f} \right\rvert}\) attains a maximum in \(\Omega\), say at \(z_0\). Since \(f\) is holomorphic, it is an open mapping, and therefore if \(D_\delta(z_0) \subset \Omega\) then \(f(D_\delta(z_0))\) contains a disc. Thus there exists a \(z\in D_\delta(z_0)\) such that \({\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert} > {\left\lvert {f(z_0)} \right\rvert}\). But this contradicts maximality of \(f\) at \(z_0\).
Corollary
If \({\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert} = 0\) on \({{\partial}}U\) and is nonconstant, then \(f\) has a zero in \(U\).
Proof
Let \(c = {\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert}\) for \(z\in {{\partial}}U\). Suppose that \(f(z)\) has no zeros in \(U\). Then \(g(z) = \frac{1}{f(z)}\) is continuous and holomorphic in \(U\). Then for all \(z_0 \in U\), \({\left\lvert {g(z)} \right\rvert} = \frac{1}{{\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert}} = \frac{1}{{\left\lvert {f(z_0)} \right\rvert}} > \frac 1 c\), since \(c = {\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert}\) for \(z\in {{\partial}}U\) implies \({\left\lvert {f(z_0)} \right\rvert} < C\). But this contradicts the maximum principle.

Proof technique: use the fact that the reciprocal is holomorphic. Note that this is stronger than \(f\) just being smaller in the interior, the modulus actually takes on the smallest value.

The Complex Logarithm

For \(x>0\), we define \(\log(x) = \int_1^x \frac 1 t ~dt\), which is the inverse of \(e^x\). For \(z\neq 0\), we’d like to define \(\log(z) = \log(re^{i\theta}) = \log(r) + i \theta\), but the argument \(\theta\) is not uniquely defined.

Theorem (Existence of Logarithm)

Suppose \(\Omega\) is simply connected with \(1\in \Omega\) and \(0\not\in\Omega\). Thin in \(\Omega\), there is a branch of the logarithm \(F(z) = \log_\Omega(z)\) such that

  1. \(F(z)\) is holomorphic on \(\Omega\).
  2. \(e^{F(z)} = z\) for all \(z\in \Omega\)
  3. \(F(r) = \log(r)\) for all \(r>0\in {\mathbb{R}}\) near 1.
Proof

Part 1:

We define \(F(z)\) as a primitive of the function

\[\begin{align*} F(z) = \int_\gamma \frac 1 w ~dw .\end{align*}\]

where \(\gamma\) is any curve in \(\Omega\) connecting \(1\) and \(z\). We have

\[\begin{align*} \frac{dF}{dz} = \frac 1 z = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{F(z+h) - F(z)}{h} .\end{align*}\]

Noting that \(F(z+h) - F(z) = \int_\eta \frac 1 w ~dw\), we can parameterize \(\eta\) as \(w = (1-s) z + s(z+h) = z + sh\). Then

\[\begin{align*} \int\eta \frac{1} {w} ~dw &= \int_0^1 \frac{1}{z+sh} ~hds \\ \implies \frac{1} {h} \int_0^1 \frac {1} {w} ~dw &= \int_0^1 \frac{1}{z + sh} ~ds \\ &= \int_0^1 \qty{\frac {1} {z} + \frac{1}{z + sh} - \frac {1} {z} }~ds \\ &= \frac {1} {z} - \frac {h} {z} \int_0^1 \frac{d}{z+sh} ~ds \\ &\overset{h\to 0}\to \frac {1} {z} .\end{align*}\]

Part 2:

Note that \(\qty{ z e^{F(z)} }' = e^{F(z)} +ze^{-F(z)} \qty{- \frac 1 z } = 0\).

Part 3:

The Fourier Transform

Recall \(\widehat{f}(\xi) = \int_{\mathbb{R}}f(x) e^{2\pi i x\ cdot \xi} ~dx\). Define \({\mathcal{F}}_a = ??\).

Definition (Decay)
\(f\in {\mathcal{F}}_a\) iff 1. \(f\) is holomorphic in the strip \(S_a = \left\{{z = x + iy {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}{\left\lvert {y} \right\rvert} < a}\right\}\). 2. There exists an \(A>0\) such that \({\left\lvert {f(x + iy)} \right\rvert} < \frac{A}{1+x^2}\).

Examples:

  • \(e^{-z^2} \in {\mathcal{F}}_a\) for all \(a\)
  • \(\frac{1}{c^2 + z^2} \in {\mathcal{F}}_a\) for all \(a > c\)
  • \(\frac {1}{\cosh(\pi z)} \in {\mathcal{F}}_a\) for \(a< \frac 1 2\).
Lemma
If \(f\in {\mathcal{F}}_a\), then \(f^{(n)}(z) \in {\mathcal{F}}_b\) for all \(b < a\).
Theorem (Boundedness of ?? Functions)
If \(f\in {\mathcal{F}}_a\), then \({\left\lvert {\widehat{f}(\xi)} \right\rvert} \leq B e^{-2\pi b {\left\lvert {\xi} \right\rvert}}\) for some constants \(b, B\).
Proof

If \(\xi = 0\), \[\begin{align*} {\left\lvert { \widehat{f}(\xi) } \right\rvert} &= {\left\lvert {\int_{\mathbb{R}}f(x) e^{2\pi i x \cdot \xi}} \right\rvert} \\ &\leq \int_{\mathbb{R}}{\left\lvert {f(x)} \right\rvert} ~dx \\ &\leq A \int_{\mathbb{R}}\frac 1 {1+x^2} ~dx \\ &= A\pi .\end{align*}\]

For \(\xi > 0\), integrate over the box \([-R, R]\times i[-b, 0]\):

Define \(g(z) = f(z) e^{-2\pi i z \cdot \xi}\). The integral over the rectangle is zero, since \(g\) is holomorphic, so we can equate \[\begin{align*} \int_R^{R-ib} f(z) e^{-2\pi i z \cdot \xi} ~dz = \int_0^b f(R - it) e^{-2\pi i (R-it)\cdot \xi} (-i)~dt \end{align*}\] We can use the estimate in \({\mathcal{F}}_a\) to obtain \[\begin{align*} \int_0^b \cdots &\leq \int_0^b \frac{A}{1+R^2} e^{-2\pi s \xi} ~ds \\ &\leq O(R^{-2}) .\end{align*}\]

Then

\[\begin{align*} \int_{\mathbb{R}}f(x) e^{-2\pi i x \cdot \xi} ~d\xi &= \int_{-\infty - ib}^{\infty - ib} \cdots ~dz\\ &= \int_{\mathbb{R}}f(x-ib) e^{2\pi i (x - ib)\cdot \xi} ~dx \\ &\leq \int_{\mathbb{R}}\frac{A}{1+x^2} e^{-2\pi b \xi} ~dx \\ &= A\pi e^{-2\pi b \xi} ,\end{align*}\]

so we can take \(B = A\pi\).

For \(\xi > 0\), the same argument works with the rectangle above the axis.

Fourier Inversion

Theorem (Fourier Inversion)
If \(f\in {\mathcal{F}}_a\), then \(f(x) = \int \widehat{f}(\xi) e^{2\pi i x\cdot \xi} ~d\xi\).
Proof

Letting \(L_1 = \left\{{x-ib}\right\}\) and \(L_2 = \left\{{x+ib}\right\}\) \[\begin{align*} I &= \int_0^\infty \widehat{f} \cdots + \int_{-\infty}^0 \widehat{f} \cdots \\ &= \int_0^\infty e^{2\pi i x \cdot \xi} \qty{ \int_{L_1} f(z) + e^{-2\pi i z \cdot \xi} ~dz } ~d\xi + \int_{\infty}^0 e^{2\pi i x \cdot \xi} \qty{ \int_{L_1} f(z) + e^{-2\pi i z \cdot \xi} ~dz } ~d\xi \\ &= \int_{L_1} \int_0^\infty e^{2\pi i x \xi - 2\pi i (s-ib)\xi} ~d\xi ~ds + \int_{L_2} f(z) \int_{-\infty}^0 e^{2\pi i x \cdot \xi - 2\pi i (s + ib)\xi} ~d\xi ds\\ & \quad \quad\text{ by absolute convergence, where } z = s-ib \\ &= \int_{L_1} f(z) \int_0^\infty e^{2\pi i (x - s + ib)\xi} ~d\xi ~ds + \int_{L_2} f(z) \int_{-\infty}^0 e^{2\pi i (x - s + ib)\xi} ~d\xi ~ds \\ &= \int_{L_1} f(z) \frac{1}{2\pi i (x - i + ib)} ~ds + \int_{L_2} f(z) \frac{1}{2\pi i (x - s - ib)} \\ &= \frac{1}{2\pi i} \int \frac{f(z)} {z - x} ~dz \\ &= f(x) ,\end{align*}\]

noting that

\[\begin{align*} \int_0^\infty e^{as} ~ds = \frac 1 a \quad\text{for }\Re(a) > 0 .\end{align*}\]

Note the similar trick: for \(\xi < 0\), move up, and \(\xi > 0\) move down to form a rectangle. Use the fact that integration along the vertical edges is zero.

Conformal Equivalence

We’ll be following Stein, around Chapter 8 currently but skip section 4. We’ll discuss Kobe’s proof of the Riemann Mapping Theorem.

Definition
A bijective holomorphic function \(f: U \to V\) is called a conformal map or biholomorphism. Given such a map, we say that \(U\) and \(V\) are conformally equivalent or biholomorphic.

Note that this gives an equivalence relation on subsets of \({\mathbb{C}}\).

Proposition (1.1)
If \(f: U \to V\) is holomorphic and injective, then for every \(z\in U\), \(f'(z) \neq 0\). In particular, the inverse of \(f\) defined on its image is holomorphic, and thus the inverse of a conformal map is holomorphic.

This is not an iff, take \(f(z) = z^2\), then \(2z\neq 0\) on \({\mathbb{C}}\setminus 0\) but \(\sqrt{z}\) has two values for every \(z\), failing to be injective.

Proof

Toward a contradiction, suppose \(f'(z_0) = 0\) for some \(z_0 \in U\). Then since \(f\) is holomorphic, we can expand about \(z_0\) to obtain \[\begin{align*} f(z) - f(z_0) = a_k(z-z_0)^j + G(z), \quad\quad a_k \neq 0,~k\geq 2 \end{align*}\] for all \(z\) near \(z_0\), where \(G(z)\) vanishes to order \(k+1\) at \(z_0\).

For sufficiently small \(w\), we write \[\begin{align*} f(z) - f(z_0) - w = F(z) + G(z) \quad\text{where}\quad F(z) = a_k (z-z_0)^k - w \end{align*}\] Because \({\left\lvert {G(z)} \right\rvert} < {\left\lvert {F(z)} \right\rvert}\) on a small disc centered at \(z_0\) and \(G(z)\) vanishes to order \(k+1\) at \(z_0\) (where \(k> 1\)), we can conclude that \(F(z)\) h as at least two distinct zeros inside this disc. Applying Rouche’s theorem, we conclude that \(f(z) - f(z_0) - w\) has at least two zeros as well. But this contradicts the injectivity of \(f\).

Example (Cayley Transform, Important)
The unit disc and upper half plane are mapped to each other via \(F(z) = {i - z \over i + z}\) with inverse \(G(w) = i {1 - w \over 1 + w}\).

Note that this is a fractional linear transformation.

Theorem (1.2)
The map \(F: {\mathbb{H}}\to {\mathbb{D}}\) is a conformal map with inverse \(D\).
Proof

Both maps are holomorphic on their domains. Any point in \({\mathbb{H}}\) is closer to \(i\) than \(-i\), and we want to show that \({\left\lvert {F(z)} \right\rvert} < 1\) for every \(z\in {\mathbb{H}}\). This also shows that \(u^2 +v^2 = 1 \implies G(w) = 0\).

Definition (Fractional Linear Transform)
A function of the form \(f(z) = {az + b \over cz + d}\) where \(ad-bc\neq 0\) is called afractional linear transformation. The determinant condition here is to insure injectivity; otherwise this just yields the constant map. Note that \(d = {bc \over a}\)
Example
\(\operatorname{GL}(2, {\mathbb{C}}), {\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{C}})\), etc
Fact
Fractional linear transformations are determined by their values on \(0, 1, \infty\). Thus they form a group \({\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{C}}) / \left\{{\pm 1}\right\} = {\text{PSL}}(2, {\mathbb{C}})\).

We can define \({\mathbb{P}}{\mathbb{C}}^1\) by taking \((u, v) \in {\mathbb{C}}^2\setminus 0\) and setting \(u\sim v\) iff \(u = \lambda v\) for \(\lambda \neq 0\). In this case, FLTs are linear maps \({\mathbb{P}}{\mathbb{C}}^1 {\circlearrowleft}\) where we send \(f(z)\) to \([a, b; c, d] \cdot [z, 1]\). Note that \(f(-d \over c) = \infty = [1, 0]\).

  • Inversion \(T(z) = {1 \over z}\).

Theorem
If \(f\) is holomorphic on \({\mathbb{C}}\setminus \left\{{z_0}\right\}\) and injective, then \(f\) is an FLT.
Proof

Up to a translation, we can assume that \(z_0 = 0\). Then \(f\) has a Laurent series expansion \(f(z) = \sum_{-\infty}^\infty a_n z^n\).

If \(f\) has an essential singularity at zero, then by Casorati-Weierstrass implies that the image of over punctured disc is dense in \({\mathbb{C}}\). In particular, \(B \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\left\{{z {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}{\left\lvert {z-1} \right\rvert} < {1 \over 2}}\right\}\) and there exists a \(\zeta \not\in B\) such that \(f(\zeta)\) in \(f(B)\). But then there exists a \(z\in B\) such that \(f(z) = f(\zeta)\), contradicting injectivity of \(f\).

If \(f\) has a pole, it must be order at most 1, otherwise the reciprocal will have a zero of order 2 and fail injectivity, and \(f\) is injective iff \(1/f\) is injective. Then the Laurent series has at most 3 terms, \(az^{-1}+ b + cz\). But \(a=0\), otherwise solving by the quadratic formula yields two roots.

We call \(f: U\to V\) biholomorphic if it admits a bijective holomorphic inverse.

Proposition
If \(f: U\to V\) is holomorphic and injective, then \(f'(z) \neq 0\), \(f\) is biholomorphic onto its image, and thus the inverse of a conformal map is also holomorphic.
Proof

We argue by contradiction and suppose \(f'(z_0) =0\) for some \(z_0 \in U\). Then \(f(z) - f(z_0) = a(z-z_0)^k + G(z)\) for all \(z\) near \(z_0\), with \(a\neq 0, k \geq 2\), and \(G\) v anishing to order \(k+1\) at \(z_0\). For \(w\) small enough, we write \(f(z) - f(z_0) - w = F(z) + G(z)\) where \(F(z) = a(z-z_0)^k - w\).


Since \({\left\lvert {G} \right\rvert} < {\left\lvert {F} \right\rvert}\) on the boundary of a small disc \(D_\varepsilon(z_0)\) and \(F\) has at least two zeros in \(D_\varepsilon(z_0)\), Rouche’s theorem implies that \(f(z) - f(z_0) - w\) has at least two zeros in this disc.


Since \(f'(z) \neq 0\) for all \(z\) in a small punctured neighborhood of \(z_0\), it follows that that roots of \(f(z) - f(z_0) - w\) are distinct. But then \(f\) is not injective, a contradiction.


Now let \(g = f^{-1}\) be the inverse of \(f\) on its range, which we can assume is \(V\). The second part of the proof follows from a Calculus argument, see slides.

Definition
Two open sets are conformally equivalent iff there exist biholomorphic functions composing to the identity.

Recall the Cayley transform \(w = F(z) = {i - z \over i + z}\) with inverse \(z = G(w) = i {1-w \over 1 + w}\).

Theorem
The map \(F: {\mathbb{H}}\to {\mathbb{D}}\) is a conformal map with inverse \(G\).
Proof (Sketch)
Use the fact that any point in \({\mathbb{H}}\) is closer to \(i\) than \(-i\), so \({\left\lvert {F} \right\rvert} < 1\). Then show \(\Im G(w) > 0\) by expanding \(w = u + iv\) and using that fact that \(u^2 + v^2 < 1\).

The Cayley transform is a special case of a FLT \(f(z) = {az + b \over cz + d}\). Note that \(f(-{d \over c}) = \infty\) is a pole, so \(f\) should be defined with values in \(\widehat{\mathbb{C}}\cong {\mathbb{CP}}^1\). Since \(\lim_{{\left\lvert {z} \right\rvert} \to \infty}\) exists, the domain is naturally \(\widehat{\mathbb{C}}\) as well.

Identify \({\mathbb{CP}}^1\) as the space of lines through \(0\) in \({\mathbb{C}}^{n+1}\). Explicitly, take \(\mathbf{v}, \mathbf{w} \in ({\mathbb{C}}^{n+1})^\bullet\) and set \(\mathbf{v} \sim \mathbf{w} \iff \mathbf{v} = \lambda \mathbf{w}\) for some \(\lambda \in {\mathbb{C}}^{\times}\). Define open sets using the quotient topology, and this yields a metric defined by \[\begin{align*} d([u], [v]) = \qty{ q - {{\left\lvert { {\left\langle {u},~{v} \right\rangle} } \right\rvert}} \over {\left\lVert {u} \right\rVert} \cdot {\left\lVert {v} \right\rVert} } .\end{align*}\]

Let \(\infty\) denote the point \((1, 0)^t \in {\mathbb{CP}}^1\), then every other point corresponds uniquely to an element of the form \((z, 1)^t\). For any \(A\in \operatorname{GL}(2, {\mathbb{C}})\), then \(A\) acts on such an element by \(L_A(a) = (az+b, cz+d)^t = {az+b \over cz + d} \in {\mathbb{C}}\) (by dividing through the second term).

Under function composition, these are Lie groups, and the map \(A \mapsto L_A\) is a group morphism. For any \(s\in {\mathbb{C}}\), \(L_{sA} = L_A\), and \(L_A = L_{A_1}\) for some matrix \(A_1\) of determinant 1, so \(A_1 \in {\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{C}})\). Finally, \(L_{A_1} = L_{A_2} \iff A_2 = \pm A_1\), so the group of FLTs is given by \({\text{PSL}}(2, {\mathbb{C}}) = {\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{C}})/ \left\{{\pm I}\right\}\).

Now consider taking \(a,b,c,d \in{\mathbb{R}}\), yielding the subgroup \({\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{R}})\). Then for any \(A\in \operatorname{GL}(2, {\mathbb{R}})\), we have \(L_A = L_{A_1}\) iff \(A_1 \in {\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{R}})\) and \(\det A > 0\). Moreover, each such \(A\) preserves \({\mathbb{H}}\).

In particular, \[\begin{align*} \frac{a z+b}{c z+d}=\frac{(a z+b)(z \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5muz\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu+d)}{(c z+d)(c \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5muz\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu+d)}=\frac{R}{P}+i y \frac{a d-b c}{P} .\end{align*}\]

with \[\begin{align*} R=a c|z|^{2}+b d+(a d+b c) x \in \mathbb{R}, P=|c z+d|^{2}>0, \quad \text { if } y>0 .\end{align*}\]

Thus \(z\in {\mathbb{H}}\implies f(z) \in {\mathbb{H}}\), and \(\operatorname{Aut}_{\mathbb{C}}({\mathbb{H}}) = {\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{R}})\). What is \(\operatorname{Aut}_{\mathbb{C}}({\mathbb{D}})\)?

We single out the transform \(\phi(z) = {z-i \over z+i}\) represented by \(A_0 \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\begin{bmatrix} 1 & -i \ 1 & i \end{bmatrix}\) Conjugating the \({\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{R}})\) action on \({\mathbb{H}}\) by \(\phi\) yields a map \(M_A: {\mathbb{D}}\to {\mathbb{D}}\).

Letting \(A \in {\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{R}})\) and computing \(A_0 A A_0^{-1}\), we find that

\[\begin{align*} A_{0} S L(2, \mathbb{R}) A_{0}^{-1}=\left\{\left(\begin{array}{cc} \alpha & \beta \\ \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\beta\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu & \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu \end{array}\right) \in G L(2, \mathbb{C}):|\alpha|^{2}-|\beta|^{2}=1\right\}=S U(1,1) .\end{align*}\]

It turns out that this is \(\operatorname{Aut}_{\mathbb{C}}({\mathbb{D}})\). It can be checked directly that for any matrix \(B\) in this group, it in fact send \({{\partial}}{\mathbb{D}}\to {{\partial}}{\mathbb{D}}\) by computing the modulus.

Recall that there are four basic types of FLT:

  • Translation
  • Rotation
  • Dilation
  • Inversion

Moreover, any FLT can be decomposed as a composition of these 4 types:

  • If \(c=0\), then \(T(z) = {a \over d}z + {b\over d}\) which is a dilation, a rotation, then a translation
  • If \(c\neq 0\), then long division yields \(T(z)=\frac{b c-a d}{c^{2}} \cdot \frac{1}{z+\frac{d}{c}}+\frac{a}{c}\).
Theorem
If \(f\) is holomorphic on \({\mathbb{C}}\setminus\left\{{z_0}\right\}\) and injective, then \(f\) is a FLT.
Proof

Up to translation, assume \(z_0 = 0\). Then \(f\) has a Laurent series expansion \(f(z) = \sum_{n=i\infty}^\infty a_n z^n\).


Case 1: If \(f\) has an essential singularity at 0, then by Casorati-Weierstrauss, the image of every punctured neighborhood of 0 is dense in \({\mathbb{C}}\).


In particular, then if \(B \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\left\{{z {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}{\left\lvert {z-1} \right\rvert} < {1 \over 2}}\right\}\), there exists a \(\zeta\not\in B\) with \(f(\zeta) \in f(B)\). But then there is a \(z\in B\) such that \(f(z) = f(\zeta)\), contradicting injectivity.


Case 2: Suppose \(f\) has a pole of order \(n\) at 0, then \(\frac 1 f\) has a zero of order \(n\) at 0. Since \(1 \over f\) is injective, we must have \(n\leq 1\) by a previous proposition showing that the derivative can not be zero.


Applying the same argument to \(f(1/z)\) we conclude that \(f(z) = \frac a z + b + cz\) for some constants \(a,b,c\in {\mathbb{C}}\). If both \(a\neq 0, c\neq 0\) then \(cz^2 + (b-w)z + a = 0\) has two roots (up to multiplicity), contradicting injectivity.


So either \(a=0\) or \(c=0\), but not both since \(f\) is not constant. But in either case, \(f\) is an FLT.

Proposition
Suppose \(f\) is holomorphic at \(z_0\). Then \(f(z) - f(z_0) = \sum_{m=n}^\infty a_m(z-z_0)^m\) with \(a_n \neq 0 \iff\) for \(\varepsilon\) small enough, there exists \(\delta > 0\) such that \(f(z) - w\) has distinct roots in \(\left\{{z{~\mathrel{\Big|}~}0 < {\left\lvert {z-z_0} \right\rvert} < \varepsilon}\right\}\) whenever \(0 < {\left\lvert {w - f(z_0)} \right\rvert} < \delta\).

This states that \(f(d_\varepsilon(z_0))\) covers \(D_\delta(w_0) \setminus\left\{{w_0}\right\}\) exactly \(n\) times. In particular, \(f\) is injective in a neighborhood of \(z_0 \iff f'(z_0) \neq 0\).

Conformal Mappings

Qual Alert: basically everything today. E.g. Show that the conformal maps \({\mathbb{C}}\to {\mathbb{C}}\) are linear.

The three basic types are translation, dilations, and rotation.

For any \(n\in {\mathbb{N}}\), the map \(z\mapsto z^n\) is conformal in the sector \(S = \left\{{z {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}0 < \arg(z) < {\pi \over n}}\right\}\). For \(0 < \alpha < 2\), the map takes \({\mathbb{H}}\) to \(\left\{{0 < \arg{z} < \alpha\pi}\right\}\).

The map \(z \mapsto {1 +z \over 1 - z}\) takes the upper half-disc \({\mathbb{D}}^+\) to the first quadrant \({\mathbb{H}}^+\). The inverse is \(w- 1 \over w +1\) which is clearly holomorphic for \(w\neq 1\), and its image is contained in the unit disc since the distance from \(w\) to \(-1\) is always greater than the distance from \(w\) to \(1\).

Note that \[\begin{align*} f\left(e^{i \theta}\right)=\frac{1+e^{i \theta}}{1-e^{i \theta}}=\frac{e^{-i \theta / 2}+e^{i \theta / 2}}{e^{-i \theta / 2}-e^{i \theta / 2}}=\frac{2 \cos \frac{\theta}{2}}{-2 i \sin \frac{\theta}{2}}=i \cot \frac{\theta}{2} \end{align*}\]

and thus as \(\theta\) travels from \(0\) to \(\pi\) along \(S^1\), \(f(e^{i\theta})\) travels from \(i\infty\) to 0.

The logarithm \(z\mapsto \log z\) (taking the branch cut along the negative imaginary axis) maps \({\mathbb{H}}\) to the strip \(\left\{{z {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}x\in {\mathbb{R}}, 0 < y < \pi}\right\}\). The inverse is given by \(w \mapsto e^w\), and as \(x\) travels from \(-\infty\) to \(0\), \(f(x)\) travels from \(\infty + i\pi\) to \(-\infty + i\pi\). When \(x\) travels from \(0\to\infty\), \(f(x)\) travels from \(-\infty_{\mathbb{R}}\to \infty_{\mathbb{R}}\).

The map \(z \mapsto \log z\) also defined as map from the half disc \({\mathbb{D}}^+\) to the half-strip \({\mathbb{S}}= \left\{{x <0, 0 < y < \pi}\right\}\). We have \([1, -1]_{\mathbb{R}}\mapsto [-\infty ,0]\) and \(S^1_+ \mapsto i[0, \pi]\).

The map \(z \mapsto -{1 \over 2}\qty{z + {1 \over z}}\) takes \({\mathbb{D}}^+ \to {\mathbb{H}}\). We have \([0, 1] \mapsto [1 ,\infty]\) and \(S^1_+ \mapsto [-1, 1]\subset {\mathbb{R}}\), and \([0, -1] \mapsto [-1, -\infty] \subset {\mathbb{R}}\).

The map \(z\mapsto \sin z\) takes \(\left\{{-\pi/2 < x < \pi/2, y>0}\right\}\) onto \({\mathbb{H}}\). Then \([-\pi/2 + i\infty, -\pi/2 + 0] \mapsto [-\infty, 1]\) and \([-\pi/2, \pi/2] \mapsto [-1, 1]\), and \([\pi/2 + 0i, \pi/2 + o\infty] \mapsto [1, \infty]\).

Just need to know these 8 examples of conformal mappings.

Automorphisms of the Disc

Lemma (Schwarz)

Let \(f: {\mathbb{D}}\to {\mathbb{D}}\) be holomorphic with \(f(0) = 0\), then

  1. \({\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert} \leq {\left\lvert {z} \right\rvert}\) for all \(z\in {\mathbb{D}}\).
  2. If for some \(z_0 \neq 0\) we have \({\left\lvert {f(z_0)} \right\rvert} = {\left\lvert {z_0} \right\rvert}\), then \(f\) is a rotation (i.e. \(f(z) = e^{i\theta}z\))
  3. \({\left\lvert {f'(0)} \right\rvert} \leq 1\) and is equality holds, \(f\) is a rotation.
Proof

  1. Expand \(f(z) = a_1 z + a_2 z^2 + \cdots\) using \(f(0) = 0 \implies a_0 = 0\). Then \(f(z)/z\) is holomorphic in \({\mathbb{D}}\) and bounded in modulus by \(1/r\) for \(r = {\left\lvert {z} \right\rvert} < 1\). By the maximum modulus principle, this is true for any \({\left\lvert {z} \right\rvert} < r\), so letting \(r\to 1\) yields (1).

  2. Since \({\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert} < 1\), the modulus of \(f(z)/z\) attains its maximum in \({\mathbb{D}}^\circ\) and thus is constant. So \(f(z) = cz\) and at \(z_0\) we have \({\left\lvert {f(z) / (z-0)} \right\rvert} = 1\), so \({\left\lvert {c} \right\rvert} = 1\) and \(f(z)\) is a rotation.

  3. If \(g(z) = f(z)/z\) then \({\left\lvert {g(z)} \right\rvert} < 1\) for all \(z\in {\mathbb{D}}\) and \(g(0) = \lim_{z\to 0} {f(z) f(0) \over z} = f'(0)\). If \({\left\lvert {f'(0)} \right\rvert} = 1\) then \({\left\lvert {g(0)} \right\rvert} =1\), ???.

We proved that \(\operatorname{Aut}{\mathbb{D}}= {\text{SU}}(1, 1)\), which preserves a certain Hermitian form and is a non-compact group. We also showed that \(\operatorname{Aut}{\mathbb{H}}= {\text{SL}}(2, {\mathbb{R}})\).

Note that the rotations \(r_\theta: z \mapsto e^{i\theta} z \in {\operatorname{Aut}}{\mathbb{D}}\). There are also functions of the form \(\psi_\alpha: z \mapsto {\alpha - z \over 1 - \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha \mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5muz}\) where \(\alpha \in {\mathbb{D}}\). It is holomorphic in \({\mathbb{D}}\) with a simple pole at \(z= 1/\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu\).

Writing \(z= e^{i\theta}\) yields

\[\begin{align*} \psi_{\alpha} \left(e^{i \theta}\right)=\frac{\alpha-e^{i \theta}}{1-\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu e^{i \theta}}=-e^{-i \theta} \frac{\alpha-e^{i \theta}}{\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu-e^{-i \theta}} \quad \Longrightarrow\left|\psi_{\alpha}\left(e^{i \theta}\right)\right|=1 .\end{align*}\]

By the MMP, \({\left\lvert {\psi_\alpha(z)} \right\rvert} < 1\) for all \(z\in {\mathbb{D}}\). The inverse can be solved for, and it turns out that \(\psi_\alpha^{-1}= \psi_\alpha\) where \(0 \rightleftharpoons\alpha\).

Theorem

\[\begin{align*} \operatorname{Aut}(\mathbb{D})=\left\{f(z)=e^{i \theta} \frac{\alpha-z}{1-\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu z}: \theta \in \mathbb{R},|\alpha|<1\right\} .\end{align*}\]

Note that this group is not compact, since it’s homeomorphic to \({\mathbb{R}}\times{\mathbb{D}}\).

Proof
Given \(f\in {\operatorname{Aut}}({\mathbb{D}})\), there must be some \(\alpha\) such that \(f(\alpha) = 0\). Consider \(g = f\circ \psi_\alpha\), then \(g(0) = 0\) and applying the Schwarz lemma yields \({\left\lvert {g(z)} \right\rvert} \leq {\left\lvert {z} \right\rvert}\) for all \(z \in {\mathbb{D}}\). Since \(g^{-1}(0) = 0\), applying this lemma again to \(g^{-1}\) shows \({\left\lvert {g^{-1}(w)} \right\rvert} \leq {\left\lvert {w} \right\rvert}\) for all \(w\in {\mathbb{D}}\). Letting \(w = g(z)\) we obtain \({\left\lvert {g(z)} \right\rvert} = {\left\lvert {z} \right\rvert}\) for all \(z\in {\mathbb{D}}\), so by Schwarz \(g(z) = e^{i\theta}z\) is a rotation. Thus \(f(z) = e^{i\theta} \psi_\alpha(z)\).

Continuing the proof from last time. Existence involved

Definition
Let \(\Omega \subset {\mathbb{C}}\) be open. A family \({\mathcal{F}}(\Omega)\) of holomorphic functions on \(\Omega\) if every sequence has a subsequence that converges uniformly on every compact subset of \(\Omega\), where the limit need not be in \({\mathcal{F}}(\Omega)\).

Proving that a family of functions is normal is a consequence of

  • Uniform boundedness
  • Equicontinuity
Definition
A family \({\mathcal{F}}\) is said to be uniformly bounded on compact subset iff for each compact \(K \subset \Omega\) there exists \(B_K > 0\) such that \[\begin{align*} {\left\lvert {f(z)} \right\rvert} \leq B_k \quad\text{for all} \quad z\in K, f\in{\mathcal{F}} .\end{align*}\]
Definition
A family \({\mathcal{F}}\) is equicontinuous if for every \(\varepsilon> 0\) there exists \(\delta > 0\) (not depending on the point) such that for all \(z, w\in K\), \[\begin{align*} {\left\lvert {z-w} \right\rvert} < \delta \implies {\left\lvert {f(z) - f(w)} \right\rvert} < \varepsilon\quad\forall f\in{\mathcal{F}} .\end{align*}\]

Examples:

  1. The family \(f_n: I \to {\mathbb{C}}\) with \({\left\lvert {f_n'} \right\rvert} \leq M\) for some fixed constant is uniformly bounded and equicontinuous (by the MVT).
  2. The family \(f_n(x) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}= x^n\) for \(x\in I\) is uniformly bounded but not equicontinuous since \(\lim_{n\to\infty} {\left\lvert {f_n(1) - f_n(x_0)} \right\rvert} = 1\) for any \(x_o \in I^\circ\).
Theorem (Montel)

Suppose \({\mathcal{F}}(\Omega)\) is uniformly bounded on compact subsets, then

  1. \({\mathcal{F}}\) is equicontinuous on every compact subset,
  2. \({\mathcal{F}}\) is a normal family.

The proof of the theorem consists of two parts:

1.Apply the Cauchy integral formula and use that \({\mathcal{F}}\) is comprised of holomorphic functions.

Note the contrast to \({\mathbb{R}}\), where \(f_n(x) = \sin(nx), {\left\lvert {f_n(x)} \right\rvert} \leq 1\) is uniformly bounded but not equicontinuous and has no convergent subsequences on any compact subinterval of \(I^\circ\).

  1. Use the fact that uniform bounded + equicontinuous implies existence of convergent subsequences by Arzela-Ascoli (which uses diagonalization).

Not complex-analytic, works in \({\mathbb{R}}\).

Definition

A sequence \(\left\{{K_\ell}\right\}\) of compact subsets is called an exhaustion of \(\Omega\) iff

  1. \(K_\ell \subset (K_{\ell+1})^\circ\) for all \(\ell\),
  2. Any compact \(K\subset \Omega\) is contained in some \(K_\ell\), and \(\cup_\ell K_\ell = \Omega\)
Lemma
Any open \(\Omega \subset {\mathbb{C}}\) admits an exhaustion.
Proof
If \(\Omega\) is bounded, take \(K_\ell = \left\{{\operatorname{dist}(z, {{\partial}}\Omega) > \frac 1 \ell}\right\}\). Otherwise, take \(\tilde K_\ell = K_\ell \cap B_\ell(0)\).

Proof of Montel’s Theorem

Proving part 1.

Let \(K \subset \Omega\) be compact, choose \(r> 0\) such that \(D_{3r}(z) \subset \Omega\) for all \(z\in K\), e.g. \(3r < \operatorname{dist}(K, {{\partial}}\Omega)\). Let \(z, w\in K\) with \({\left\lvert {z-w} \right\rvert} < r\) and let \(\gamma = {{\partial}}D_{2r}(w)\).

Then Cauchy’s integral formula yields \[\begin{align*} f(z)-f(w)=\frac{1}{2 \pi i} \int_{\gamma} f(\zeta)\left[\frac{1}{\zeta-z}-\frac{1}{\zeta-w}\right] d \zeta .\end{align*}\]

Then since \(\xi \in \gamma\) and \({\left\lvert {z-w} \right\rvert} < r\), we have

\[\begin{align*} \left|\frac{1}{\zeta-z}-\frac{1}{\zeta-w}\right|=\frac{|z-w|}{|\zeta-z||\zeta-w|} \leq \frac{|z-w|}{r^{2}} .\end{align*}\]

Letting \(B\) be the uniform bound on \({\mathcal{F}}\) and using \({\left\lvert {\gamma} \right\rvert} = 4\pi r\), we can apply this estimate to obtain

\[\begin{align*} |f(z)-f(w)| \leq \frac{1}{2 \pi} \frac{2 \pi r}{r^{2}} B|z-w| .\end{align*}\]

Then \(f\) is uniformly Lipschitz with the constant given above, and the family is equicontinuous.

Application: show that derivative uniformly bounded implies function uniformly bounded by applying Cauchy’s integral formula.

Proving part 2.

Let \(\left\{{f_n}\right\}\) be a sequence in \({\mathcal{F}}\) and \(K\subset \Omega\) compact. Choose a dense sequence \(\left\{{w_j}\right\}\), and use uniform boundedness to obtain a subsequence \(\left\{{f_{n, 1} }\right\}\) such that \(\left\{{f_{n, 1}(w_1)}\right\}\) converges. Repeat these to get \(\left\{{f_{n, j}(w_j)}\right\}\) all converge, and set \(g_n = f_{n, n}\). The claim is that equicontinuity implies \(g_n\) converges uniformly on \(K\).

Given \(\varepsilon>0\), choose \(\delta\) from equicontinuity and note that \(K \subset D_\delta(w_1) \cup\cdots \cup D_\delta(w_J)\) for some \(J\) by density of \(\left\{{w_i}\right\}\) and compactness of \(K\). Pick \(N \gg 0\) such that \[\begin{align*} {\left\lvert {g_m(w_j) - g_n(w_j)} \right\rvert} < \varepsilon\forall j=1,2,\cdots, J .\end{align*}\]

Then any \(z\in K\) is in some \(D_\delta(w_j)\), then \[\begin{align*} \begin{aligned} \left|g_{n}(z)-g_{m}(z)\right| \leq \left|g_{n}(z)-g_{n}\left(w_{j}\right)\right|+\left|g_{n}\left(w_{j}\right)-g_{m}\left(w_{j}\right)\right|+\left|g_{m}\left(w_{j}\right)-g_{m}(z)\right| <& 3 \epsilon \end{aligned} ,\end{align*}\]

so \(\left\{{g_n}\right\}\) converges uniformly on \(K\).

Goal: put together pieces for the Riemann mapping theorem.

Today: normal families. Recall that normal families on \(\Omega\) are holomorphic functions for which every sequence uniformly on every compact subset of \(\Omega\). The family is uniformly bounded iff for every \(K\) there exists a \(B_K\) bounding \(f\) in \(K\), and is equicontinuous iff they are continuous with a parameter \(\delta\) uniform for the family.

We had Montel’s theorem: families that are uniformly bounded on compact subsets are equicontinuous and normal. This used Arzela-Ascoli and a diagonalization argument.

Theorem (Hurwitz)
Suppose \(g_n\) are holomorphic and nonzero on \(\Omega\), then if \(g_n \to g\) uniformly on compact subset, then either \(g \equiv 0\) or \(g\) is nonzero on \(\Omega\).
Proof
The limit function \(g\) is holomorphic on \(\Omega\) by the Weierstrass theorem. If \(g\not\equiv 0\), then the zeros of \(g\) are isolated. If \(\gamma \sim 0\) is a simply curve on which \(g\neq 0\), \(g'_n \to g'\) and hence \(g_n' / g_n \to g'/g\) uniformly on \(\gamma\). By the argument principle, for \(n\gg 0\) the number of zeros of \(g_n, g\) enclosed by \(\gamma\) are equal. Since \(g_n \neq 0\), the theorem follows.
Corollary (Hurwitz)
If \(g_n\) are holomorphic and injective, then either \(g\) is injective or constant.
Proof
Fix \(w\in \Omega\) and apply Hurwitz to \(g - g(w)\) on \(\Omega \setminus \left\{{w}\right\}\).
Proof (of part (B) of Riemann Mapping)

By Montel’s theorem, \({\mathcal{F}}(\Omega)\) is normal since \({\left\lvert {f} \right\rvert} < 1\) for all \(f\in {\mathcal{F}}\). Let \(M = \sup{g'(z_0) {~\mathrel{\Big|}~}g\in {\mathcal{F}}} \leq M\). By definition, we can find a sequence \(g_n\) such that \(\lim g_n'(z_0) = M\). By normality, there exists a subsequence uniformly convergent on compact subsets to some function \(f\).


In particular, \(M < \infty\) since otherwise this would yield a simple pole for \(f\) (which is holomorphic) and \(f'(z_0) = M\). By Hurwitz, \(f\) is either injective or constant because the subsequence is injective. But since \(f' = M > 0\), \(f\) is not constant.


Moreover, since \(f(z_0) = \lim g_n(z_0) = 0\) and \(f'(z_0) = M > 0\), \(f\) injective implies \(f\in {\mathcal{F}}\). This gives the existence of \(f\in{\mathcal{F}}\) such that \(g' \leq f'\) at \(z_0\) for all \(g\in {\mathcal{F}}\).

Proof (of part (C) in Riemann Mapping)

We want to show that \(f(\Omega) = {\mathbb{D}}\). Toward a contradiction, suppose not, then there exists a \(w_0 \in {\mathbb{D}}\setminus f(\Omega)\). We will construct a function \(g_1 \in {\mathcal{F}}\) with \(g_1' > f'\) at \(z_0\), which is a contradiction.

The function \(-\psi_{w_0}(f(z)) = {f(z) - w_0 \over 1 - \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5muw\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_0 f(z)}: \Omega \to {\mathbb{D}}\) is holomorphic, injective (since all such \(\psi\) are), and nonvanishing since \(w_0 \not\in f(\Omega)\). Thus there is a branch of the square root for which \(g(z) \mathrel{\vcenter{:}}=\sqrt{-\psi_{w_0}(f(z))}: \Omega \to {\mathbb{D}}\) is injective.

Finally, normalize \(g\) so that its derivative at \(z_0\) is positive and real by setting \[\begin{align*} g_1(z) = { {\left\lvert {g'(z_0)} \right\rvert} \over g'(z_0)} \qty{g(z) - g(z_0) \over 1 - \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mug(z_0)\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu g(z) } .\end{align*}\]

Then \(g_1\) has the same properties as \(g\) with \(g_1 = 0, g_1' > 0\) at \(z_0\). The first claim is easy to check, and the second follows from using \({\frac{\partial }{\partial z}\,} \qty{z - \alpha \over 1 - \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha \mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5muz} = {1 - {\left\lvert {alpha} \right\rvert}^2 \over \qty{1 - \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\alpha \mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5muz}^2 }\) and applying the chain rule.

We now compare \(f'\) and \(g'\) at \(z_0\). Note that \(f = 0, f' > 0, g^2 = -w_0\) at \(z_0\). Take \({\frac{\partial }{\partial z}\,} g^2\) to obtain \[\begin{align*} 2 g(z) g^{\prime}(z)=\frac{1-\left|w_{0}\right|^{2}}{\left(1-\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5muw\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu_{0} f(z)\right)^{2}} \cdot f^{\prime}(z) .\end{align*}\]

Evaluate at \(z=z_0\) to obtain \[\begin{align*} 2 g\left(z_{0}\right) g^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right)=\left(1-\left|w_{0}\right|^{2}\right) f^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right) \Rightarrow\left|g^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right)\right|=\frac{1-\left|w_{0}\right|^{2}}{2\left|g\left(z_{0}\right)\right|} f^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right) .\end{align*}\]

Combining this with the previous formula obtained from the chain rule \[\begin{align*} g_{1}^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right)=\frac{\left|g^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right)\right|}{1-\left|g\left(z_{0}\right)\right|^{2}}=\frac{1-\left|w_{0}\right|^{2}}{2\left|g\left(z_{0}\right)\right|} \cdot \frac{f^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right)}{1-\left|g\left(z_{0}\right)\right|^{2}} \\ &=\frac{1-\left|w_{0}\right|^{2}}{2 \sqrt{\left|w_{0}\right|}} \cdot \frac{f^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right)}{1-\left|w_{0}\right|} \quad \text{ using } g^2(z_0) = - w_0 \\ &=\frac{1+\left|w_{0}\right|}{2 \sqrt{\left|w_{0}\right|}} f^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right) \\ & > f^{\prime}\left(z_{0}\right) .\end{align*}\]

Where we’ve used the Schwarz inequality, \[\begin{align*} \frac{1+\left|w_{0}\right|}{2 \sqrt{\left|w_{0}\right|}}>1 .\end{align*}\]

But then \(g_1' > f'\), a contradiction.

Note that this is a long proof in the book – seven pages!

Definition

In this case, \(a_k(x_0)\) is given by the \(k\)th Taylor coefficient.

Theorem

Then the Riemann mappying function \(f\) extends to a homeomorphism \(\mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5muf\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu: \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\Omega \mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu\to \mkern 1.5mu\overline{\mkern-1.5mu\mathbb{D}\mkern-1.5mu}\mkern 1.5mu\).

Proof: Apply the previous theorem to the real analytic part of \({{\partial}}\Omega\), then map these diffeomorphically onto open arcs in \({{\partial}}{\mathbb{D}}\). Let \(J_1, J_2\) be real analytic curves in \({{\partial}}\Omega\) meeting at \(p\) and let \(I_1, I_2\) denote their images in \({{\partial}}{\mathbb{D}}\):


We want to show that \(I_1\) meets \(I_2\) and their endpoints \(q_1, q_2\) coincide. We have \(\ell(r) = \int_{\gamma_r} {\left\lvert {f'} \right\rvert}\), where \(\gamma_r\) is as in the figure, and applying Cauchy-Schwarz yields \[\begin{align*} {\left\lvert {\ell(r)} \right\rvert}^2 &\leq_{CS} \int 1^2 \cdot \int {\left\lvert {f'} \right\rvert}^2 \\ &\leq 2\pi r \int {\left\lvert {f'} \right\rvert}^2 \\ \implies {\ell(r)^2 \over r} \leq 2\pi \int {\left\lvert {f'} \right\rvert}^2 .\end{align*}\]

Next goal: Picard’s theorem. Best proof is Picard’s original, which comes from Ahlfors.

Recall the notion of covering maps from topology: for \(\pi: E\to X\) is a covering map iff for every \(p\in X\) there is a \(U_x\) such that \(\pi^{-1}(U) = {\coprod}S_j \subset E\), where \(\pi(S_j) = U\) is a homeomorphism.

Proposition
If \(E, X, Y\) are connected and locally path-connected and \(E\xrightarrow{\pi} X\) is a covering map, then if \(Y\) is simply connected then any \(f: Y\to X\) lifts to \(\tilde f: Y\to E\).
Proposition
Any continuous lift of a holomorphic map is also continuous.
Proof
Take \(q\in U, p= f(q) \in {\mathcal{O}}\). Let \(V \ni p\) be a neighborhood such that \(\pi^{-1}(V)\) satisfies the covering condition with the projections holomorphic homeomorphisms. Then \(\tilde f(q) \in S_k\) for some \(k\), and \(\tilde f^{-1}(S_k) = f^{-1}V = U_1\) is a neighborhood of \(q\in U\). So the restrictions of \(\tilde f, \pi^{-1}\circ f\) to \(U_q\) are equal and thus \(\tilde f\) is holomorphic on each \(U_q\).
